A multiplicative partition of a number \( n \) is a way of writing \( n \) as a product of one or more integers, each greater than 1, where the order of the factors does not matter. Given that 64 is \( 2^6 \), all multiplicative partitions of 64 will consist of powers of 2. The number of multiplicative partitions of 64 is equivalent to the number of integer partitions of 6, where each part is at least 1. This is because each factor in the multiplicative partition is a power of 2, and the exponents of 2 must sum to 6. The integer partitions of 6 are as follows: 1. [6] 2. [5, 1] 3. [4, 2] 4. [4, 1, 1] 5. [3, 3] 6. [3, 2, 1] 7. [3, 1, 1, 1] 8. [2, 2, 2] 9. [2, 2, 1, 1] 10. [2, 1, 1, 1, 1] 11. [1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1] Each of these partitions corresponds to a multiplicative partition of 64. For example: - The partition [6] corresponds to \( 2^6 \). - The partition [5, 1] corresponds to \( (2^5) \times (2^1) = 32 \times 2 \). - The partition [4, 2] corresponds to \( (2^4) \times (2^2) = 16 \times 4 \). - And so on. Thus, the number of multiplicative partitions of 64 is equal to the number of integer partitions of 6, which is 11. \[ \boxed{11} \]
